============================================================
 GIT - GETTING STARTED
 A working reference: what each command means and when you use it
============================================================

1. THE MENTAL MODEL

------------------------------------------------------------
Git tracks the history of a folder. You take snapshots
("commits") of your files over time, and you can move between
them, compare them, and sync them to a server.

Four places your work lives:

- Working directory  the actual files you edit on disk.
- Staging area (the "index")  changes you've marked to go
    into the next snapshot.
- Local repository  the committed history in the hidden
    .git folder.
- Remote  the copy on a server (GitHub, Azure DevOps) that
    others can reach.

Everyday loop:  edit  ->  stage  ->  commit  ->  push

1. ONE-TIME SETUP

------------------------------------------------------------
Run once per machine (global), or inside a repo to override
just for that repo. Identity is stamped onto every commit.

  git config --global user.name "..."
      Sets the name attached to your commits.
  git config --global user.email "..."
      Sets the email attached to your commits.
  git config --global init.defaultBranch main
      Makes new repos start on a branch called main.
  git config --list
      Shows all current settings and where each came from.

1. STARTING A REPOSITORY

------------------------------------------------------------
  git init
      Turns the current folder into a Git repo (creates .git).
  git clone <url>
      Downloads an existing remote repo, with full history,
      into a new folder.
  git status
      Shows what's changed, what's staged, and the current
      branch. Run it constantly.

Tip: git status is the command you run most. It tells you
exactly where you are before every other action.

1. THE DAILY LOOP - STAGE, COMMIT, PUSH

------------------------------------------------------------
  git add <file>
      Stages one file's changes for the next commit.
  git add .
      Stages everything changed in the current folder and below.
  git restore --staged <file>
      Unstages a file (keeps edits, removes it from next commit).
  git commit -m "message"
      Snapshots everything staged, with a short message.
  git commit -am "message"
      Stages already-tracked files and commits in one step
      (skips new files).
  git push
      Uploads your local commits to the remote.
  git pull
      Downloads remote commits and merges them into your branch.
  git fetch
      Downloads remote commits but does NOT merge - look first.

A typical session:
  git status                 # what changed?
  git add Defender/ASR-SpotCheck.ps1
  git status                 # confirm only what you meant is staged
  git commit -m "Add ASR spot-check tier filter"
  git pull                   # bring in anyone else's work first
  git push                   # send yours up

Write commit messages in the imperative ("Add...", "Fix...",
"Update...") and describe the why, not just the what. Future-you
reading git log will thank you.

1. BRANCHING - WORKING WITHOUT BREAKING MAIN

------------------------------------------------------------
A branch is an independent line of work. Make changes on a
branch, then merge them back into main when ready. This keeps
main always-working.

  git branch
      Lists branches; the current one is marked with *.
  git switch -c <name>
      Creates a new branch and moves onto it.
  git switch <name>
      Moves to an existing branch.
  git merge <name>
      Pulls another branch's commits into the one you're on.
  git branch -d <name>
      Deletes a branch once it's merged.
  git push -u origin <name>
      Pushes a new branch up and links it for future plain push.

Older guides use git checkout for switching branches - git
switch is the newer, clearer command that does the same thing.

1. INSPECTING HISTORY AND CHANGES

------------------------------------------------------------
  git log --oneline
      Compact one-line-per-commit history.
  git log --oneline --graph --all
      Visual branch/merge history across all branches.
  git diff
      Shows unstaged changes (working dir vs last commit).
  git diff --staged
      Shows what's staged and about to be committed.
  git show <commit>
      Shows the full change introduced by one commit.
  git blame <file>
      Shows who last changed each line and in which commit.

1. UNDOING THINGS

------------------------------------------------------------
Safe rule: prefer commands that preserve history over ones
that rewrite it, especially on anything already pushed.

  git restore <file>
      Discards unstaged edits (reverts to last commit).
      Irreversible - the edits are gone.
  git restore --staged <file>
      Unstages without losing edits.
  git commit --amend
      Rewrites the most recent commit (fix a message or add a
      forgotten file). Don't amend pushed commits.
  git revert <commit>
      Creates a NEW commit that undoes an old one. Safe on
      shared history.
  git reset --soft HEAD~1
      Undoes the last commit but keeps changes staged.
  git reset --hard HEAD~1
      Undoes the last commit AND discards its changes.
      Destructive - use with care.

Rule of thumb: revert is the safe public undo; reset --hard is
the dangerous private one. Never rewrite history (amend / reset)
on commits others have already pulled.

1. KEEPING SECRETS OUT (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

------------------------------------------------------------
Git remembers everything. A credential committed once stays in
history even after you delete the file - so never commit it in
the first place.

- Keep a .gitignore listing secret patterns (*.key,*.pem,
    .env, *.clixml, secrets*.json) so they're never staged.
- Run a scanner (gitleaks) as a pre-commit hook to block
    accidental secrets, with a CI scan as a server-side backstop.
- Always run git status before git commit and confirm nothing
    sensitive is staged.
- If a secret does get committed: rotate the credential
    immediately - removing the file is not enough, because it
    remains in history until the history is rewritten.

1. QUICK REFERENCE CARD

------------------------------------------------------------

# setup (once)

  git config --global user.name "Name"
  git config --global user.email "<you@pharo.org>"

# start

  git init                 # new repo here
  git clone <url>          # copy a remote repo

# daily loop

  git status               # what changed
  git add <file> | .       # stage
  git commit -m "msg"      # snapshot
  git pull                 # get others' work
  git push                 # send yours up

# branches

  git switch -c <name>     # new branch
  git switch <name>        # change branch
  git merge <name>         # merge into current

# inspect

  git log --oneline        # history
  git diff                 # unstaged changes

# undo

  git restore <file>       # discard edits
  git revert <commit>      # safe undo (new commit)
